Hey everyone! Thrilled to announce a new album I made this year with my new bestie💚 @timlefev 💚
@night_plow first single $1.49 Day is out now. Hit link in bio to pre order!!

@wearebusybodies WABB-139: Night Plow - S/T

Night Plow is the coming together of complete strangers Tim Lefebvre and Gregory Macdonald. On the 24th February, the duo are set to release their self-titled debut album via We Are Busy Bodies. 

Taking in influences including Kraftwerk, Andy Stott, Vangelis, Photek, Hans Zimmer, Radiohead, Undo K From Hot and The Avalanches, Night Plow is an insuperable symphony of 21st century sounds that crosses any music border.

They say, “never meet your heroes”. Well add to that, “never meet your collaborator.” Lefebvre and Macdonald both contributed parts to the 2021 critically acclaimed album ‘Lee “Scratch” Perry’s Guide To The Universe’ by New Age Doom and despite having never met in person and only speaking on the phone once, decided they shared enough common musical ground between them to step forward and start a brand new experimental project. Lefebvre would improvise beats and bass lines in his studio in Tuscon and then send Macdonald snippets of ideas which he would then edit into songs by adding synths and effects and then mixing them into more realized finished tracks. On the collaboration, Macdonald adds, “I was feeling the effects of Covid entering its second year and was getting a bit restless, and a long-distance collaboration with someone I’d never met but had great admiration and respect for seemed like the perfect thing to make it through the cold Canadian winter. I get excited by experimental music and trying new things, so I was pleased when Tim suggested we start a brand-new project. I loved what he did on the LSP/New Age Doom album and was thrilled when Tim liked the first thing I sent him and suggested we start a new collab”

The album is out February 24, 2023. There is an exclusive colour variant in our Bandcamp store. First single, $1.49 Day is out today.

“Forming after they made contributions to New Age’s 2021 album ‘Lee "Scratch" Perry's Guide To The Universe’, talented bass player Tim Lefebvre collaborates with Sloan keyboardist Gregory Macdonald as Night Plow. The bass and beats are the key attraction, underpinning an enervating vision of electronica and cyberpunk. For fans of Radiohead, Kraftwerk and the ‘Blade Runner’ soundtrack.”
Album comes out Feb 24 on @wearebusybodies

I’ve been getting a lot of questions about the bass sound in our latest Odd Meter Drums preview, so I decided to break down the process of taking a @timlefev bass loop in 4/4 and mangling it into something completely different in 13/8.

The new album I made with world-renowned bass giant @timlefev is called Night Plow and it is being released online and gorgeous vinyl on Feb 24 by @wearebusybodies. The new single is called Amanda and showcases Tim’s signature bass grooves but also the funkiest hi hat since the Isley Brothers. @night_plow

Co composed with @timlefev and @verabluemusic this song is part of the first wave of two leaves music, an improvisational experiment in expression. Laying waste to obvious songwriting techniques, I wanted to create a living music, like a waterfall of ideas, not to be repeated or “arranged” for their memorable “hook” but rather like clouds to allow ideas to pass by whilst being observed for their beauty. Just like the way we may notice a plant in nature as we walk but don’t fall to our knees in admiration of the living god of earth. #acid #opera #ai #bmi #emi #dmt #lsd #lsa #classA #plant #vegan #model #moose #kiln #flint #sherpa

I'm reposting @earthquakerdev on the new Zoar but i tracked @gracelougenmusic thru this pedal into a @voxamplification AC30 at @sonicranch and this pedal was far from "another" fuzz pedal. So dialable and Massive sounding. 

In their words:

And now, without further ado, let’s go!
Zoar™ is a medium-high gain discrete distortion (using only transistors; no opamps or diodes in here!) with a passive 3-band EQ that has that touch sensitive amp-like quality to it that everyone craves. It has been finely tuned to create a highly tweakable hi-fi and modern sounding distortion that is both instantly familiar and delightfully unique. From the defined sparkle and tightness of an overdrive to low-medium gain fuzz that’s perfect for drop tuned guitars and basses, Zoar does it all. Dial in and control every nuance of your tone from jangly on-the-verge of break up to blowing the walls out heavy saturation.
Zoar has six knobs that allow you to truly customize your sound with the Level, Weight, Gain, Bass, Middle, and Treble controls. The Gain control goes from the edge of break up all the way over the cliff into the crunchy, grinding abyss. The character of the distortion is heavily dependent on the setting of the Weight control as well as the pickup type and further fine-tuned by the EQ section.

Ok! My social media video game is very Rusty but thought i would take a stab at a demo for the @earthquakerdev ZOAR. @gracelougenmusic can testify. You'll hear it on the new @grosh_band record a lot.(sorry for the rick james quote too. Well, not really)

Whose Hat Is This? - welcome to the Heartcore Family!
@timlefev @kebbiwilliams #jjjohnsondrums #tylerfalcongreenwell @kokayi @whosehatisthisband 
Tim Lefebvre: Electric Bass, Acoustic Bass, Keys, Guitar 
Tyler “Falcon” Greenwell: Drums, Percussion
JJ Johnson: Drums, Percussion
Kebbi Williams: Saxophone, Flute

New album „Ponyboy“ out on April 26th 2024 on @weareheartcorerecords 
___________

From a serendipitous jam in Berlin to the sun-drenched plains of El Paso, Whose Hat is
This? has woven a sonic tapestry fueled by improvisation, flavor and unhindered talent.

Their story begins, fittingly, with a question. JJ Johnson, the band’s enigmatic drummer, found
himself staring at a ten gallon cowboy hat perched on a tom during a late-night jam
session at Berlin’s A-trane. „Whose Hat is This?“ he called out, the question becoming
their moniker, an apt symbol for their embrace of the unplanned and the unexpected.

That night, two hours of untamed musical exploration unfolded, captured unknowingly
on tape. The raw energy, the fearless interplay, it begged to be shared. Thus, their self-
titled debut, a vinyl-only gem, was born.

KOKAYI was weaved into the fabric of their improvisations, leading to „Everything’s
Ok,“ a second live album recorded at Baltimore’s 8x10 club. With KOKAYI on board,
the musical conversations came vocal as well, and the band’s East Coast tour
cemented their reputation as pioneers of sonic spontaneity.

Ponyboy, their debut studio album, releasing in April 2024 on Heartcore Records is a snapshot of their current journey, a testament
to the electrifying spark that ignites when musical minds collide without a map, an
homage to the days when innocence of not knowing birthed innovations and a passion
for discovery.

Kebbi Williams: Saxophone, Flute
